    {
      "id": "label_literacy",
      "title": "How to Read Labels Better",
      "summary": "Label literacy is the skill of using the Nutrition Facts panel, ingredient list, serving size, and claims together instead of relying on any one part of the package. A food may look healthy because of one nutrient or one front-of-package phrase, but the full label often tells a more complicated story. The best readers compare similar products, check servings, and look for patterns rather than slogans.\n\nThis concept turns label reading into a practical habit. Instead of asking whether a product is simply healthy or unhealthy, a label-literate shopper asks what the food is made of, how much is in a serving, and how it compares to alternatives. That matters because many packaged foods are designed to look better than they are at a quick glance. Learning to read labels reduces that confusion and makes later concepts like serving-size tricks and front-of-package claims much easier to understand.",
      "sections": [
        {
          "title": "Context",
          "body": [
            "Most people do not read food labels from top to bottom in a careful way. They glance at the front, maybe check calories, and move on. Label literacy is the ability to slow down enough to interpret the whole package. It is especially important because food companies know that shoppers often make decisions quickly.",
            "A label-literate consumer does not treat one nutrient as the whole story. For example, a snack might be low in fat but high in sugar, or high in protein but also high in sodium. Learning to compare multiple features at once is the real skill that nutrition education tries to build."
          ]
        },
        {
          "title": "Key figures & forces",
          "body": [
            "The main figure here is the consumer, but dietitians, public health educators, and regulatory agencies all help shape label literacy. FDA guidance gives people the basic framework, while health organizations teach how to use it in real life. Food companies, meanwhile, design labels to capture attention as efficiently as possible.",
            "The key forces are attention, comparison, and tradeoff. People have limited time and mental energy, so they often focus on one clue. Label literacy improves judgment by making it easier to compare similar foods and see the tradeoffs clearly."
          ]
        },
        {
          "title": "Core idea",
          "body": [
            "The core idea is that good label reading is contextual. No single number tells the whole story. A food that looks impressive for one reason may be weak in another area, so the reader has to consider the whole package.",
            "Label literacy is also about skepticism without paranoia. The goal is not to assume every label is deceptive. The goal is to know where to look, what to compare, and how to make a decision based on evidence rather than packaging design."
          ]
        },
        {
          "title": "Actions / how it works",
          "body": [
            "A practical label-reading routine starts with the serving size, then the calories, then the nutrients of concern for that food category. After that, the ingredient list can confirm whether the product is mostly made of familiar whole ingredients or heavily processed components. Finally, compare similar products side by side.",
            "This method works because it reduces the influence of front-of-package marketing. If two cereals look similar on the shelf, the label-literate shopper checks fiber, added sugar, and ingredient order before choosing. That turns a vague impression into a reasoned decision."
          ]
        },
        {
          "title": "Consequences / impact",
          "body": [
            "Better label literacy helps people choose foods that fit their goals and needs. It is also useful for families, schools, and institutions that buy large amounts of packaged food. The more people understand labels, the less power superficial packaging has.",
            "This concept sits at the center of the topic because it prepares readers for the more specific label tactics that follow. Serving-size tricks and front-of-package claims only make sense once someone knows how to read the whole label first."
          ]
        },
        {
          "title": "Connections",
          "body": [
            "This concept bridges the basics of the Nutrition Facts panel and the more specific tricks that follow. It is the practical skill layer of the topic. The next concept on serving-size tricks shows why even accurate numbers can mislead if the serving is framed strategically."
          ]
        }
      ]
