      "summary": "Policy and reform shape how much food labels can help consumers. Regulators like the FDA set rules for the Nutrition Facts panel, ingredient lists, and many claims, but packaging can still be confusing or visually manipulative. Front-of-package labeling proposals, clearer standards, and consumer education all aim to make labels easier to use.\n\nThis concept matters because misleading labels are not only a personal reading problem. They are also a design and regulation problem. If labels are hard to interpret, then public policy can improve the information environment. Better labeling would not eliminate the need for label literacy, but it could reduce the number of traps people face. In that sense, reform is about making the truth easier to see.",
